Visited for the first time last week for lunch after moving to the neighborhood. I lived next to Joe's pizza prior to moving here, so I was looking for a go to place to grab a solid slice. Customer service was good, the guy at the window and I talked for a bit and he thanked me for supporting the business. I brought home nearly one of every slice for my partner and I to try. Price is a bit steep if I'm honest, it's hard to swallow spending $4.75 on a slice, but ingredient quality seemed appropriate. The scicillian was a bit dry, but tasty and the pepperoni were my favorite type. If it was fresher it would of been ideal. The grandma was a bit overpowering with garlic, and I love garlic. Grandma slices are my normal go to, but it won't be here. Mushroom and spinach slices were good. And BY FAR the best was the special slice with the olives, sopresata, and onions. OH MY.... seriously so good if you like olives. That's a must try. Price point makes it less of a daily staple, but I will definitely be back for much more. Especially the olive slice. Keep it up and good luck in these hard times!

Well run Sicilian eatery.  Their menu may seem limited, as compared to the 'regular' pizza joint, but they keep things Sicilian traditional, which is kind of nice on an informational level--we do like feeling genuine--more importantly; everything they offer is as close to perfection, as is possible; in this age where $1 slices, no matter how doughy, draws a crowd. They call it Neapolitan, I call it New York Pizza, either way it's my favorite by far in recent memory, spanning pizza north of 100th Street to Washington Heights, Manhattan, and the swath of BK between Bushwick to East NY.  Thin crackly outercrust, enough sauce to feel some juice but not drenched or too sweet, which can ruin an otherwise good slice), and ohhhh, the cheese.  Haha. They also make Sicilian, which is good, albeit not my thing.  There's more to their menu, go, mange, and enjoy.

Absolutely love Fazio’s.  We moved in down the street this summer and Fazio’s is honestly one of the reasons we felt confident about moving here. The Sicilian slices are a meal and then some.  Hearty, delicious, and crispy.  Haven’t tried their pasta dishes, but the salads are freshly made to order and just as flavorful. Good pizza! Crust has a good crunch to it, but still fluffy. Lots of sauce and great cheese. Not too heavy. Perfect amount of cheese, rather than some slices that use so much cheese that all you’re eating is mozzarella. I had a sicilian slice with toppings and a regular slice with eggplant and left feeling satisfied but not weighed down and heavy. Also, to address some other reviews:  1) The crust gets a little burnt here and there on the edges but thats how some of the better pies are. Supposed to be like that so that it remains crispy where it has the most sauce. 2) The cheese doesnt cover the entire slice/pie. If it did that would be way much and weigh it down, overwhelming the sauce and crust. 3) Theres plenty, plenty of sauce. Cant dispute that. 4) Yes it could have some more meat/toppings but thats super subjective. Personally it could use a just little but more, but not a dealbreaker.
